          {
            "spanish": "yo tengo",
            "english": "I have"
          },
          {
            "spanish": "tú tienes",
            "english": "you have"
          },
          {
            "spanish": "él/ella tiene",
            "english": "he/she has"
          },
          {
            "spanish": "nosotros tenemos",
            "english": "we have"
          },
          {
            "spanish": "ellos/ustedes tienen",
            "english": "they/you all have"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "lesson",
        "heading": "TENER Expressions",
        "content": "Spanish uses TENER where English uses 'to be' for physical states and feelings:\n                              → tener sueño = to be sleepy (to have sleep)",
        "examples": [
          {
            "spanish": "tener hambre",
            "english": "to be hungry (to have hunger)"
          },
          {
            "spanish": "tener sed",
            "english": "to be thirsty (to have thirst)"
          },
          {
            "spanish": "tener frío",
            "english": "to be cold (to have cold)"
          },
          {
            "spanish": "tener calor",
            "english": "to be hot (to have heat)"
          },
          {
            "spanish": "tener sueño",
            "english": "to be sleepy (to have sleep)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "lesson",
        "heading": "TENER QUE + Infinitive",
        "content": "To express obligation ('have to'), use TENER QUE + infinitive verb:\n                  \n   ✏️ Exercise: Translate: 'She has to study'",
        "examples": [
          {
            "spanish": "Tengo que trabajar",
            "english": "I have to work"
